   <text>
      <body>
        <div type="letter"> 
        <opener><dateline><date when="1916-02-19">February 19, 1916</date></dateline>
<salute>My dear <persName key="mary_aldis">Mrs. Aldis</persName>:</salute></opener>
<p>Your letter has just come, and indeed if you enjoyed our brief time together, you can faintly imagine how much I enjoyed it. Your real devotion to art, and your deep interest in it, was immensely refreshing and filled me with joy.</p>
<p>I certainly sent you <title level="a">“The Grocery,”</title> but it must have got lost in some way, and it will probably appear months hence from the <orgName key="deadLetterOffice">Dead-Letter Office</orgName>. I will bring it and <title key="turnpike" level="a">“Off the Turnpike”</title> when I come.</p>
<p>Just now I am in the throes of writing my lectures for <placeName key="newYork">New York</placeName>, one of them being the one I am going to deliver in <placeName key="chicago">Chicago</placeName>. So forgive a short letter, which however takes the best of good wishes. Until the 10th, then,</p>
<salute>Sincerely yours</salute>,
        </div>
      </body>
